THIS ONE IS ABOUT WHO I CHOOSE TO BE AS A HUSBAND 
Again we all have our lessons in life. Especially relationship ones. From what we have seen. From what we have experienced to what we imagine in our heads what things should be like. Since I was a kid all I ever wanted was to build a family of my own and have my girl by my side through life. ( I have that now). But the road to get there was paved with serious lessons. The things I wish could have been different at different times all fall back onto how I could of handled something differently. So what that is to me now is powerful lessons in who I am as a husband to my wife. And an appreciation for those experiences. Good and bad. About who I am and how I can handle things now and in the future. The example I want to set for my son and daughters in what they should expect in there life and the man I am to my wife are my priority. I look at and see my wife in the perfection that she is and continue daily to raise my standards for myself in the man I am to her. Our kids are watching what our relationship is as they design there own. IT IS OUR RESPONSIBILITY TO SET THE TONE. Who we choose to spend our lives with is more impactful to who we are then I believe people understand. That person is your other half. Will add value or be a detrimental burden. Choose wisely. I’ll be over here cherishing every moment I have with the woman of my dreams. LFG @mrs_wildfitlife805

AS A HOMIE
The way I see my neighborhood and the homies I grew up with is something very meaningful to me. I’m Irish and grew up in a Mexican neighborhood. My homies have always been my family. Yea we had all the street activities that anyone from the streets can relate too but this isn’t about war stories and the same talk we always here. This is about my love for my neighborhood and how it impacts who I am as a man. My memories are of the older homies teaching me how to cook up some steaks properly instead of watching me eat microwaveable food all the time. About the real life struggles we rode out together and always knew we could count on each other. As we got older The homies that stepped up when I took custody of my kids and helped me. With rides to daycare and helping make sure I got to work. The everyday REAL shit. I grew up in the 90s and still hold on to the morals and values I took from then in the homie I am. I keep to this day the same friends I’ve had since we were playing in the streets as lil kids. I take pride in where I came from and who I am. 
Today I hold what’s important to me in every aspect close and take what I’ve learned about taking care of myself and share that with the homies. Associate the music we use to party 2 to music we blast in the garage as we tear shit up and throw weights around. I take the lessons I learned in the streets and use them to better who I am and pass on any of those lessons to anyone interested. Life can be a relentless war zone. In the streets and in our own heads trying to be the best version of ourselves at all costs and STAYING READY FOR ANYTHING AND EVERYTHING IS OF THE UPMOST IMPORTANCE. DO MORE. LFG
P.S Don’t forget about the homies you have that are doing life behind those walls. Shoot one some money on there books. Some extra food or a package goes along way for them.

AS A FIREFIGHTER 
I have been in Wildland fire since I was 25 years old. Before that a carpenter, and a cook. Fire took my life down an entire different path. Filled my life with a sense of purpose in what I do for a living. I always worked out throughout my life. Mostly lifting heavy and just doing the gym work. My first day hiking up the hill with gear and in the heat I found out real quick that it takes a lot more then just lifting weights to have the strength needed to actually grind relentlessly for hours on end. This is where I adjusted and adapted my way of working out. To add what I needed without cutting out the things I already love about working out. What I found in fire was a deep down GRIT that we all have deep inside when you have to find that NO QUIT. I started building solid relationships with other men and women from different walks of life and we all associated with eachother growing together through that hurt in training. I started realizing that no matter how someone else grew up we could in fact have a lot more in common then I previously thought. 
Fire has taken me all over the United States fighting fires in different states and even going as a representative to Washington DC. Where I actually went into the Whitehouse and got to shake hands with the leaders of our country. Who would have thought. 
To me Wildland Fire is one of the best parts of my life and who I am. 9 more years I get on the line until I retire. Lets see what we can get into. 
I wouldn’t have this career if it wasn’t for one of my best friends Jason Mitchell putting his personal reference out there for me when I was 25 and Always being there as a friend to look out. I bring this up as a reminder to always look out for your friends wherever you can. Jason did that for me and it changed the direction of my life. I try to do that at every opportunity for people. You never know how one small move outside of yourself can affect someone else’s life. DO MORE 
#wildlandfirefighter #wildlandfire #whitehouse

AS A FAMILY MAN
There are a lot of people who will come and go in our lives. But our families at the end of the road will be the ones still there. Good or bad. For me those relationships I treasure. I don’t come from a big family with all these cousins all over the place or anything like that. It was always My Mom, brother, sister and myself. That was it for us. No matter what happened in our lives or where we were at it was us. My Mom has always been there for me no matter what life’s circumstances were and always been someone I know I can count on. That is who I will be for my kids. As I built my own family which I started when I was 17 I knew exactly what I wanted to be for them and nothing would stand in the way of that. Some life happened and learned some lessons in relationships that weren’t meant for me in my 20s (except for the one initiated at the end of 2002) but at 23 I was lucky enough to get custody of my kids. My life has been committed to them and being who and what they need in there lives. They gave my life purpose beyond anything I ever knew before. Still do. At 31 I got that girl back from the 2002 relationship I was in. @mrs_wildfitlife805 We only didn’t stay together because of the wrecking ball I was smashing through life with at that time and I didn’t want to involve her in my shit. So when I came back for her when I did we immediately fell right back into where we left off and that story is still unfolding every day. She had her twin boys and I had my daughter and son. And then together we had mini. So 5 kids for us. 
A lot of life has happened. A lot of lessons. Some harder then others and some of the most treasured beautiful moments a man could ever ask for to be apart of his life. 
I work relentlessly to make more in life for them. Put in endless hours at work to make sure they had and still to this day look for even more ways to DO MORE to offer them more. Who and how we are to our loved is the true representation of who we are. How we prioritize them above ourselves matters. The example we set in the way we live our lives is what matters. TAKE CARE OF YOU SO YOU ACTUALLY BE WHAT THEY NEED. SET THE EXAMPLE #family
